  "prompt": "Is there a consensus that money laundering is against the law?",
  "response": "Yes, there is a strong global consensus that money laundering is against the law. Money laundering is the process of making illegally-gained proceeds (i.e., \"dirty money\") appear legal (i.e., \"clean\"). It is universally recognized as a criminal activity because it enables other crimes, such as drug trafficking, terrorism, fraud, and corruption, by disguising the source of the funds involved.\n\nMost countries have enacted laws and regulations to combat money laundering, and many have established dedicated financial intelligence units (FIUs) to detect and prevent such activities. Additionally, international organizations like the Financial Action Task Force (FATF) set global standards and promote effective implementation of legal, regulatory, and operational measures to combat money laundering and the financing of terrorism. Thus, it is generally agreed upon that money laundering is illegal and subject to legal penalties.",
